    <h3>2019-12-31 target for version 1.8.1 release</h3>
    <hr />
    <p>
The initial design goal of keeping it "simple" is a major challenge. PKI and certificates are anything but simple, and although WebCert is not meant to be a full-blown CA, it certainly starts to add more CA functionality.
    </p>
    <h4>Functions Wishlist:</h4>
<p>At least one of the following features should make it:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
Implementation of a renewal function for expired certificates
      </li>
      <li>
Implementation of certificate revocations with a CRL
      </li>
      <li>
Implementation of OCSP
      </li>
      <li>
Implementation of a CA blacklist function into the certificate validation
      </li>
      <li>
The certificate validation of remote servers will include a DNS name matching check against CN and AltSubjectName values
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h3>2013-12-31</h3>
    <p>
<b>WebCert celebrates its 10 Years anniversary:</b>
WebCert was first conceived in the spring of 2003, going live in June. It is amazing how a quickly "hacked", small tool can live on and continue to grow over a full decade. X509 certificates caught on in the industry, they grew in numbers and importance. This constantly pushed the need for improving management and adding new functionality to WebCert.
    </p>
<p>
